{"type":"text","timestamp":1777814123219,"sessionID":"ses_212083eacffev1P0BHgU1Vq1DB","part":{"id":"prt_dedfaaab6001vCk8jCm5jtZV9F","messageID":"msg_dedfa94700018rhMDDzLi1zr7j","sessionID":"ses_212083eacffev1P0BHgU1Vq1DB","type":"text","text":"I have analyzed the current microarchitecture and identified three high-value `micro_opt` improvements that cleanly complement each other to boost both IPC and Fmax:\n\n1. **JAL Early Resolution (IPC Boost):** JAL currently resolves in the EX stage, incurring a multi-cycle penalty. By calculating the target and redirecting the IF stage directly from the ID stage, we drop the JAL penalty to 0 bubbles.\n2. **Precise Load-Use Checking (IPC Boost):** The hazard unit currently blindly checks the `rs1` and `rs2` instruction bits against `rd`, regardless of whether the instruction actually reads those registers (e.g. JAL, LUI). Passing `rs1_ren` and `rs2_ren` from the decoder eliminates these false 1-cycle stalls.\n3. **Single Multiplier Sharing (Fmax & Area Boost):** The ALU is currently synthesizing three separate 32-bit multipliers for `mul_ss`, `mul_uu`, and `mul_su`. Replacing them with a single shared 33x33 signed multiplier significantly reduces DSP/LUT usage, which eases routing congestion and improves Fmax.\n\nI have written the hypothesis YAML to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r1s0.yaml`. The orchestrator can now proceed with the implementation phase.","time":{"start":1777814121142,"end":1777814123216}}}
