{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777814094303,"sessionID":"ses_212083f5dffeQXwd6j53xnUCXY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"tool_write_qPRvBUVpGSVdhQoFmRek","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r1s1\ntitle: \"Structural Resource Sharing for ALU and EX Adders\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current design independently instantiates three 64-bit multipliers, four 32-bit dividers, and redundant 32-bit adders in the EX stage. This massively inflates LUT and DSP usage (~9880 LUTs on Tang Nano 20K), causing severe routing congestion and reducing Fmax.\nhypothesis: |\n  Consolidating the multipliers and dividers into single shared instances, and reusing existing adders in the EX stage (using `alu_result` instead of `jalr_sum`, and `branch_target` for JAL), will drastically reduce area and routing delay. The improved structural efficiency will increase Fmax and directly boost CoreMark iter/sec.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 15\n  confidence: high\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: |\n      Implement structural sharing for heavy arithmetic operators.\n      1. Replace `mul_ss`, `mul_uu`, `mul_su` with a single `logic signed [65:0] mul_res`. Create 33-bit operands `mul_a` and `mul_b`, sign-extended or zero-extended based on the `op`, and compute `mul_res = $signed(mul_a) * $signed(mul_b)`. Map the appropriate slices of `mul_res` to the `ALU_MUL*` outputs.\n      2. Unify the four independent `/` and `%` instances into a single shared unsigned divider and remainder block. Compute absolute values `div_a_abs` and `div_b_abs` (accounting for `op` sign), compute `div_res_abs = div_a_abs / (div_b_abs == 32'b0 ? 32'd1 : div_b_abs)` and `rem_res_abs = div_a_abs % (div_b_abs == 32'b0 ? 32'd1 : div_b_abs)`. Apply final sign corrections inside the `case(op)` branches (preserving the `0x80000000/-1` and `b=0` trap logic).\n      Keep the `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` logic untouched.\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: |\n      Eliminate redundant 32-bit adders by reusing existing computed sums.\n      1. The ALU already computes `rs1 + in.imm` for JALR, so the standalone `jalr_sum` adder is entirely redundant.\n      2. The `in.pc + in.imm` sum for JAL is already identical to `branch_target`.\n      3. Remove the `jalr_sum` variable and update `jump_target` to reuse these values:\n         `jump_target = in.ctrl.is_jalr ? {alu_result[31:1], 1'b0} : branch_target;`","filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gemini-3_1-pro-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r1s1.yaml"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gemini-3_1-pro-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r1s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r1s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777814094287,"end":1777814094300}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":"**Exploring Microarchitecture Improvements**\n\nI'm currently focusing on identifying potential structural enhancements for the RV32IM core, specifically aiming to boost its CoreMark performance on the Tang Nano 20K FPGA. My initial exploration involves analyzing the existing microarchitecture to pinpoint bottlenecks and opportunities for optimization, with a keen eye on instruction fetch and execution stages.\n\n**Optimizing Fetch Logic**\n\nI'm examining the instruction fetch stage, specifically how it interacts with control flow. My current focus is on reducing pipeline stalls caused by branches by investigating the feasibility of implementing a simpler, earlier branch resolution mechanism.\n\n**Refining Fetch and Branch Logic**\n\nI'm currently investigating how to optimize instruction fetch, specifically by looking into earlier branch resolution. My aim is to reduce pipeline stalls by mov