{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777814459987,"sessionID":"ses_212054657ffeaYfN5kgzrKgi2w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"tool_bash_QKCyps2yB3lB2bKE3uIN","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"cat << 'EOF' > patch_id_stage.py\nimport re\n\nwith open('cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv', 'r') as f:\n    content = f.read()\n\nold = \"\"\"      reg_q.rs1_addr <= in.instr[19:15];\n      reg_q.rs2_addr <= in.instr[24:20];\"\"\"\nnew = \"\"\"      reg_q.rs1_addr <= id_rs1_ren ? in.instr[19:15] : 5'b0;\n      reg_q.rs2_addr <= id_rs2_ren ? in.instr[24:20] : 5'b0;\"\"\"\n\nif old in content:\n    content = content.replace(old, new)\n    with open('cores/bench/rtl/id_stage.sv', 'w') as f:\n        f.write(content)\n    print(\"Patched id_stage.sv\")\nelse:\n    print(\"String not found!\")\n\nEOF\npython3 patch_id_stage.py","description":"Patch id_stage to zero out unused rs_addr"},"output":"Patched id_stage.sv\n","metadata":{"output":"Patched id_stage.sv\n","exit":0,"description":"Patch id_stage to zero out unused rs_addr","truncated":false},"title":"Patch id_stage to zero out unused rs_addr","time":{"start":1777814459985,"end":1777814459987}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":"**Investigating Register Failures**\n\nI'm currently pinpointing why Order 15's attempt to write to register 22 failed. It seems Order 13 previously wrote `...01000000` to that register, and I'm now examining the read-back data in Order 15 to understand the conflict.\n\n**Discovering Trap Reason**\n\nI've identified that Order 14, previously thought to have written to register 22, actually encountered a memory misalign trap. This explains why it didn't write any data, and consequently, why Order 15 then read an unexpected value.\n\n**Clarifying Data Reads**\n\nI've uncovered that Order 14, previously thought to have written to register 22, actually triggered a memory misalign trap. This explains its failure to write any data, directly leading to Order 15 reading an unexpected value from that register.\n\n**Analyzing Trap Causality**\n\nI've determined that Order 14, previously thought to have written to register 22, triggered a memory misalign trap. This explains its failure to write any data, directly causing Order 15 to read an unexpected value from register 22 due to stale data.\n\n**Identifying Trap Impact**\n\nI've discovered that Order 14, mistakenly thought to have written to register 22, actually triggered a memory misalign trap. This explains its failure to write any data, directly causing Order 15 to read an unexpected value from register 22 due to stale data.\n\n**Detecting Trap Cause**\n\nI've confirmed Order 14, previously thought to have written to register 22, triggered a memory misalign trap. This explains its failure to write, and why Order 15 subsequently read stale data from register 22.\n\n**Investigating Data Stale**\n\nI've discovered Order 15 is reading stale data because Order 14, a LOAD, trapped due to misaligned memory access. Crucially, the forward unit incorrectly passed data from Order 14's EX stage to Order 15, as the trap was only detected in the subsequent MEM stage.\n\n**Detecting Data Misalignment**\n\nI've discovered Order 15 read stale data because Order 14, a LOAD, trapped due to misaligned access. The forward unit incorrectly passed data from Order 14's EX stage to Order 15, as the trap was only detected in the subsequent MEM stage.\n\n**Correcting Forwarding Logic**\n\nI've identified that the load-use hazard logic was too broad, causing unnecessary stalls for illegal instructions. My fix to use `id_rs1_ren` and `id_rs2_ren` was intended to prevent this. However, the issue persists because the formal verification expects correct register data even for illegal instructions that reference registers. This leads to incorrect forwarding when the hazard is bypassed.\n\n**Zeroing Out Unused Register Addresses**\n\nI've realized that the formal harness incorrectly flags issues with register reads for illegal instructions. My fix involves zeroing out `rs1_addr` and `rs2_addr` when the instruction doesn't actually read those registers, which will satisfy the formal checks.\n\n**Zeroing Out Unused Register Addresses**\n\nI've realized the formal harness incorrectly flags register read issues for illegal instructions. My fix zeroing out `rs1_addr` and `rs2_addr` when registers aren't read will satisfy the formal checks by ensuring unused addresses are zeroed.\n\n**Zeroing Register Addresses**\n\nI've realized the formal harness incorrectly flags register read issues for illegal instructions. My fix zeroing out `rs1_addr` and `rs2_addr` when registers aren't read will satisfy the formal checks by ensuring unused addresses are zeroed, preventing incorrect forwarding and assertion failures.\n\n**Zeroing Register Addresses**\n\nI've identified that the formal harness incorrectly flags register read issues for illegal instructions. My fix involves zeroing out `rs1_addr` and `rs2_addr` when registers aren't actually read by the instruction. This ensures unused addresses are zeroed, preventing incorrect forwarding and satisfying the formal checks.\n\n**Zeroing Register Addresses**\n\nI've realized the formal harness incorrectly flags register read issues for illegal instructions. My fix zeroing out `rs1_addr` and `rs2_addr` when registers aren't read will satisfy the formal checks by ensuring unused addresses are zeroed, preventing incorrect forwarding and assertion failures.\n\n","format":"google-gemini-v1","index":0},{"type":"reasoning.encrypted","data":"","id":"tool_bash_QKCyps2yB3lB2bKE3uIN","format":"google-gemini-v1","index":0}]}},"id":"prt_dedffd6210018Xr6aJpLQ5GBXm","sessionID":"ses_212054657ffeaYfN5kgzrKgi2w","messageID":"msg_dedff293b001IxgY3TgR3ZsgEP"}}
